\section{RWTS reload}

When the game needs to load new level data, it calls the RWTS reload entry
at \$BE00. This routine turns the drive motor on, saves the screen,
copies the loader code from the language card backup (\$D000--\$D7FF)
back to \$5000--\$57FF, calls the loader entry at \$5000 to load the
next level data set, then restores the screen and returns.

<<rwts reload>>=

        ORG $BE00
RWTS_RELOAD:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Reload the loader from language card and call it to load level data.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   LDR_SLOT — disk slot * 16
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Turns on drive motor, scrolls screen up to save it,
        ;   copies $D000-$D7FF back to $5000-$57FF (restoring the loader),
        ;   calls LOADER_ENTRY, then jumps to SCREEN_RESTORE.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   $5000-$57FF (loader restored), $A0-$A1, screen buffer
        ; Clobbers: A, X
        LDX LDR_SLOT
        LDA DISK_MOTOR_ON,X    ; Turn motor on
        JSR SCROLL_UP          ; Save screen content
        INC $A0                ; Adjust buffer pointer
        INC $A1
        LDX LDR_SLOT

; Self-modifying loop: copy $D000-$D7FF to $5000-$57FF (restore loader).
        LDA #$D0
        STA .src+2             ; Patch source page
        LDA #$50
        STA .dst+2             ; Patch dest page
        LDX #$00
.src:   LDA $D000,X
.dst:   STA $5000,X
        INX
        BNE .src
        INC .src+2
        INC .dst+2
        LDA .dst+2
        CMP #$58               ; Done when dest reaches $5800
        BNE .src

; Call loader (saves ZP, loads level data, restores ZP, returns).
        JSR LOADER_ENTRY
JMP_TO_RESTORE:
        JMP SCREEN_RESTORE     ; Restore screen and return
@ %def RWTS_RELOAD JMP_TO_RESTORE

\section{Sector data reader}

An alternate sector data reader at \$BE37 reads odd/even nibble-encoded
data directly into memory via the [[$A2]]/[[$A3]] pointer. It reads
256-byte blocks in a loop, checking for a \$D4 marker between blocks,
and repeats until a page counter at [[$A1]] reaches zero.

Note: the entry at \$BE37 overlaps with the last byte of the [[JMP]]
instruction at \$BE35. The byte \$BE at that position serves double duty
as both the high byte of the JMP target and the LDX abs,Y opcode.

<<nibble reader>>=

        ORG $BE38
; Read odd/even nibble-encoded sector data into memory via $A2/$A3, $A1 pages.
; $BE37 is the 3rd byte of the JMP above. When branched to, $BE serves
; as the LDX abs,Y opcode: LDX $C08C,Y.
NIBBLE_READER = $BE37               ; Overlaps with 3rd byte of JMP above

; Bytes $BE38-$BE3B are part of the LDX $C08C,Y instruction at $BE37
; (overlap with JMP high byte) plus its BPL loop. We emit them as raw
; bytes since they're not independent instructions.
        DC.B $8C,$C0           ; ...continuation of LDX $C08C,Y at $BE37
        DC.B $10,$FB           ; BPL NIBBLE_READER ($BE37)
        ROL                    ; Shift odd nibble into position
        STA $A0                ; Save partial
.wait_even:
        LDA DISK_DATA,X        ; Wait for even nibble
        BPL .wait_even
        AND $A0                ; Combine odd+even
        STA ($A2),Y            ; Store decoded byte
        INY
        BNE NIBBLE_READER      ; Loop 256 times (branches to $BE37)

; Between blocks: check for $D4 sync marker.
        ASL $FFFF              ; Timing pad (6 cycles)
.wait_sync:
        LDA DISK_DATA,X
        BPL .wait_sync
        CMP #$D4               ; Sync byte between sectors
        BNE RWTS_RELOAD+$10    ; Mismatch: retry from page setup ($BE10)
        INC $A3                ; Next destination page
        DEC $A1                ; Decrement block count
        BNE NIBBLE_READER      ; More blocks: continue reading
        JMP SCREEN_PRE_RESTORE ; Done: restore screen
@ %def NIBBLE_READER

\section{Applesoft and Monitor patches}

Several jump vectors patch into Applesoft BASIC and Monitor ROM routines.
These include a 16-bit division routine using \$DA/\$DB as divisor and
\$CE/\$CF/\$E6/\$E7 as dividend/result.

<<applesoft patches>>=

        ORG $BE60
; Trampoline: redirect BELL to Monitor BELL2.
PATCH_BELL:
        JMP MON_BELL2           ; Redirect to Monitor bell

; Trampoline: HPLOT with Y=$77 (hi-res page 2 base).
PATCH_HPLOT:
        LDY #$77
        JMP AS_HPLOT_ENTRY      ; Applesoft HPLOT entry

; Trampoline: HPLOT with Y=$7B (alternate base), shares JMP with PATCH_HPLOT.
PATCH_HPLOT2:
        LDY #$7B
        BNE PATCH_HPLOT+2       ; Share JMP $E3E0

DIVIDE:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; 16-bit unsigned division via repeated subtraction.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   $DA/$DB — divisor (16-bit)
        ;   $CE/$CF — dividend (16-bit, shifted out as quotient)
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Calls Applesoft GETNUM to parse parameters. If divisor is
        ;   zero, jumps to Applesoft division-by-zero error. Otherwise
        ;   performs 16 iterations of shift-and-subtract division.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   $CE/$CF — quotient, $E6/$E7 — remainder
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   $CE, $CF, $E6, $E7
        ; Clobbers: A, Y
        JSR AS_GETNUM           ; Applesoft GETNUM
        LDA $DA                 ; Divisor low
        BNE .do_div
        LDA $DB                 ; Divisor high
        BNE .do_div
        JMP AS_DIV_ZERO_ERR     ; Division by zero error
.do_div:
        ASL $CE                 ; Shift dividend left
        ROL $CF
        ROL $E6
        ROL $E7
        LDA $E6
        CMP $DA
        LDA $E7
        SBC $DB
        BCC .no_sub
        STA $E7
        LDA $E6
        SBC $DA
        STA $E6
        INC $CE                 ; Quotient bit
.no_sub:
        DEY
        BNE .do_div
        RTS

; Padding
        HEX FF FF FF FF FF FF
@ %def PATCH_BELL PATCH_HPLOT PATCH_HPLOT2 DIVIDE

\section{Screen management}

The screen management routines handle saving and restoring the hi-res
display during disk loads. SCREEN\_PRE\_RESTORE calls a game callback
at \$5C00 before restoring. SCREEN\_RESTORE scrolls the screen back
down, clears hi-res lines using address tables at \$7380/\$7440,
and clears the hi-res screen holes.

<<screen restore>>=

        ORG $BEA0
; Call game screen callback at $5C00, then fall through to SCREEN_RESTORE.
SCREEN_PRE_RESTORE:
        JSR GAME_SCREEN_RTN     ; $5C00 (game callback)

SCREEN_RESTORE:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Restore hi-res screen after a disk load.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   Buffer at $4000 — saved screen lines from SCROLL_UP
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Scrolls saved lines back to screen via SCROLL_DN, clears
        ;   hi-res lines $21-$BB using address tables at $7380/$7440,
        ;   then zeroes screen hole bytes ($x78-$x7F, $xF8-$xFF)
        ;   across hi-res page 2 ($4000-$5FFF).
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   Hi-res page 2, $A0-$A3
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
; Scroll screen back down, then clear hi-res lines.
        JSR SCROLL_DN
        LDX #$21                ; Start at line $21
.clear_lines:
        LDA GAME_LINE_TBL_LO,X  ; Line address table low
        STA $A0
        LDA GAME_LINE_TBL_HI,X  ; Line address table high
        STA $A1
        LDY #$27                ; 40 bytes per line
        LDA #$00
.clear_byte:
        STA ($A0),Y
        DEY
        BPL .clear_byte
        INX
        CPX #$BC                ; End at line $BC
        BCC .clear_lines

; Clear hi-res screen "holes" (the unused bytes at the end of each line
; group in hi-res memory: bytes $78-$7F and $F8-$FF of each page).
        LDA #$00
        LDY #$40
        STA $A0                 ; Start at $4000
        STY $A1
        LDX #$20                ; 32 pages ($4000-$5FFF)
.clear_page:
        LDY #$78               ; Clear $78-$7F
.clear_hole1:
        STA ($A0),Y
        INY
        BPL .clear_hole1
        LDY #$F8               ; Clear $F8-$FF
.clear_hole2:
        STA ($A0),Y
        INY
        BMI .clear_hole2
        INC $A1                 ; Next page
        DEX
        BNE .clear_page
        RTS

; Data bytes (purpose unclear, possibly sprite data or flags).
        HEX 80 83
@ %def SCREEN_PRE_RESTORE SCREEN_RESTORE

\section{Copy ROM to language card}

Copies the Apple II ROM (\$D000--\$FFFF) into language card RAM. This is
the same operation performed by boot1's phase 3. Used by the reset handler
to restore the language card state.

<<copy rom to lc>>=

        ORG $BEE0
COPY_ROM_TO_LC:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Copy Apple II ROM ($D000-$FFFF) into language card RAM.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Enables LC bank 1 write mode with ROM readable, then
        ;   copies each byte from ROM into LC RAM via indirect
        ;   addressing. Loops from $D000 until high byte wraps to $00.
        ;   Write-protects LC on exit.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   Language card RAM ($D000-$FFFF), $A0/$A1
        ; Clobbers: A, Y
        LDA LC_BANK1_RWROM      ; Enable LC writes, read ROM
        LDA LC_BANK1_RWROM      ; (must read twice)
        LDY #$00
        LDA #$D0
        STY $A0
        STA $A1                 ; Pointer = $D000
.copy:
        LDA ($A0),Y             ; Read from ROM
        STA ($A0),Y             ; Write to LC RAM
        INY
        BNE .copy
        INC $A1
        BNE .copy               ; Loop until $A1 wraps ($FF+1=$00)
        BIT LC_BANK1_ROROM      ; Write-protect LC
        RTS

; Jump to game routine.
        JMP GAME_ROUTINE_1255
@ %def COPY_ROM_TO_LC

\section{Reset handlers}

Four entry points display different error characters on reset, using the
BIT abs trick to skip [[LDA #imm]] instructions:
`R' (\$D2), `P' (\$D0), `L' (\$CC), or `!' (\$A1).

The common handler copies ROM to language card, reinitializes the Monitor,
clears the screen, clears memory from \$BD00 downward (with beeps via the
speaker toggle), then reboots into the slot's ROM using a PHA/PHA/RTS trick.

<<reset handlers>>=

        ORG $BF00

RESET_R:
        LDA #$D2
        DC.B $2C                ; BIT abs (skip next 2 bytes)
RESET_P:
        LDA #$D0
        DC.B $2C                ; BIT abs (skip next 2 bytes)
RESET_L:
        LDA #$CC
        DC.B $2C                ; BIT abs (skip next 2 bytes)
RESET_BANG:
        LDA #$A1

; Common reset handler.
        ; Restore language card, clear screen, wipe memory $0800-$BDFF
        ; with speaker beeps, then reboot via slot ROM.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   A — error character to display (from RESET_R/P/L/BANG)
        ;   LDR_SLOT — boot slot * 16
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   $0800-$BDFF (zeroed), language card RAM, screen
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        PHA                     ; Save error character
        JSR COPY_ROM_TO_LC      ; Restore language card
        JSR MON_INIT            ; Initialize monitor
        JSR MON_HOME            ; Clear screen
        JSR MON_NORMAL          ; Normal text mode
        PLA
        STA TEXT_SCREEN          ; Display error char at top-left

; Clear memory from $BDFF downward to $0800, with beeps.
.clear_outer:
        LDY #$00
        TYA
.clear:
.clear_page = *+2
        STA $BD00,Y             ; Self-modifying: page decremented
        INY
        BNE .clear              ; Inner loop: fill one page
        DEC .clear_page         ; Next page down
        BIT SW_SPEAKER          ; Beep
        LDA .clear_page
        CMP #$08                ; Stop at $0800
        BCS .clear_outer        ; Outer loop: next page

; Set reset vector to slot ROM and reboot.
        STA $03F3               ; Low byte (= $08, harmless value)
        STA $03F4               ; Checksum (invalid, forces cold start)
        LDA LDR_SLOT            ; Get slot * 16
        LSR                     ; Derive slot ROM page $Cn
        LSR
        LSR
        LSR
        ORA #$C0
        SBC #$00                ; A = $Cn (carry was set from LSR)
        PHA                     ; Push high byte
        LDA #$FF
        PHA                     ; Push low byte ($FF)
        RTS                     ; "Return" to $CnFF+1 = $Cn00 (slot ROM)

; Loader persistent state (used as variables, not code).
LDR_TRACK       = $BF48         ; Current track
LDR_SLOT        = $BF49         ; Slot * 16
LDR_PHASE       = $BF4A         ; Boot phase counter

; Emit the initial values at these locations.
        PHP                     ; $BF48: initial value $08
        RTS                     ; $BF49: initial value $60 (slot 6 * 16)
        BRK                     ; $BF4A: initial value $00
@ %def RESET_R RESET_P RESET_L RESET_BANG LDR_TRACK LDR_SLOT LDR_PHASE

\section{Screen scroll routines}

Two screen scroll routines save and restore hi-res screen content during
disk loads. SCROLL\_UP copies 32 hi-res lines to a buffer at \$4000.
SCROLL\_DN copies from the buffer back to the screen, then fills the
bottom 4 text lines from \$0300 data.

SCROLL\_UP has two entry points: a preamble at \$BF4B that checks whether
to use a game scroll handler, and the main entry at \$BF50 which overlaps
with the operand bytes of a [[JMP $28A0]] instruction (the byte sequence
\$A0 \$28 reads as [[LDY #$28]] when entered at \$BF50).

<<scroll up>>=

        ORG $BF4B
SCROLL_UP_PRE:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Save 32 hi-res screen lines to a buffer at $4000.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   A — if $FF, perform scroll; otherwise jump to game handler at $28A0
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Checks A for $FF; if not, delegates to game scroll handler.
        ;   Otherwise copies 32 lines (40 bytes each) from hi-res page 2
        ;   to the buffer at $4000, using SCREEN_ADDR_TBL for source
        ;   addresses. SCROLL_UP ($BF50) is an alternate entry that
        ;   overlaps with the JMP operand bytes (LDY #$28).
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   $4000-$44FF, $A0-$A3
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        TAY                     ; Save A
        INY
        BEQ .skip               ; If A was $FF, skip to main scroll
        JMP GAME_SCROLL_HANDLER ; Otherwise jump to game scroll handler

; The JMP $28A0 above is $4C $A0 $28. Entry at $BF50 sees $A0 $28 = LDY #$28.
SCROLL_UP = SCROLL_UP_PRE + 5  ; $BF50: overlapping entry (LDY #$28)

.skip:
        LDA #$40
        STY $A0                 ; Dest low = 0 (Y=0 from BEQ path)
        STA $A1                 ; Dest high = $40
        LDX #$00
.copy_line:
        LDA SCREEN_ADDR_TBL,X  ; Line address low
        STA $A2
        LDA SCREEN_ADDR_TBL+1,X ; Line address high
        STA $A3
        LDY #$27                ; 40 bytes per line
.copy_byte:
        LDA ($A2),Y             ; Read from screen
        STA ($A0),Y             ; Write to buffer
        DEY
        BPL .copy_byte
        CLC
        LDA $A0
        ADC #$28                ; Advance buffer by 40 bytes
        STA $A0
        BCC .no_carry
        INC $A1
.no_carry:
        INX                     ; Next address pair
        INX
        CPX #$40                ; 32 lines (64 bytes in table)
        BCC .copy_line
        RTS
@ %def SCROLL_UP_PRE SCROLL_UP

<<scroll dn>>=

        ORG $BF7F
SCROLL_DN:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Restore 32 hi-res screen lines from the buffer and fill bottom rows.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   Buffer at $4000-$44FF — saved screen data from SCROLL_UP
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Copies 32 lines (40 bytes each) from the buffer back to
        ;   hi-res page 2 in reverse order using SCREEN_ADDR_TBL,
        ;   then fills the bottom 4 screen rows (188-191) from $0300 data.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   Hi-res page 2, $A0-$A3
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDY #$00
        LDA #$45
        STY $A0                 ; Source = $4500 (buffer after scroll data)
        STA $A1
        LDX #$3E                ; Start from last line pair
.copy_line:
        LDA SCREEN_ADDR_TBL,X
        STA $A2
        LDA SCREEN_ADDR_TBL+1,X
        STA $A3
        LDY #$27
.copy_byte:
        LDA ($A0),Y             ; Read from buffer
        STA ($A2),Y             ; Write to screen
        DEY
        BPL .copy_byte
        SEC
        LDA $A0
        SBC #$28                ; Move buffer pointer back
        STA $A0
        BCS .no_borrow
        DEC $A1
.no_borrow:
        DEX
        DEX
        BPL .copy_line

; Fill bottom 4 hi-res rows (188-191) from $0300 data.
        LDX #$27                ; 40 bytes
.fill_bottom:
        LDA BOTTOM_ROW_DATA,X
        STA HIRES2_ROW188,X     ; Row 188
        STA HIRES2_ROW189,X     ; Row 189
        STA HIRES2_ROW190,X     ; Row 190
        STA HIRES2_ROW191,X     ; Row 191
        DEX
        BPL .fill_bottom
        RTS
@ %def SCROLL_DN

